Data Description

The data come from a study on childhood obesity. Pregnant mothers were enlisted and then each child was followed from birth to two years old. The purpose of this analysis is to understand what role the human microbiome plays in childhood obesity. The human microbiome refers to the different bacteria that live inside/on humans. The following variables are available in the dataset.

  • id: id of subject
  • weight_born: weight at birth (in kg)
  • height_born: height at birth (in cm)
  • weight_2yr: weight at 2 years
  • height_2yr: height at 2 years
  • child_buccal_fb: Firmicutes-to-Bacteroidetes ratio in the child’s mouth. These are two phyla of bacteria. The ratio of their abundences are thought to play an important role in obesity.
  • child_gut_fb: Firmicutes-to-Bacteroidetes ratio in the child’s gut.1
  • mom_buccal_fb: Firmicutes-to-Bacteroidetes ratio in the mother’s mouth.
  • child_buccal_alpha: Alpha diversity of types of bacteria in the child’s mouth. The alpha diversity is a summary of how diverse the types of bacteria are (i.e. are there lots of different types of bacteria).
  • child_gut_alpha: Alpha diversity in the child’s gut.
  • mom_buccal_alpha: Alpha diversity in the mother’s mouth.
  • Treatment: There were two treatments as part of this study, with labels “Safety” and “Parenting”. “Safety” refers to the control group, while “Parenting” means the treatment group where the parents received nutritional training.
  • Antibiotic: Did the child receive antibiotics in the first two years.
  • Gender: Gender of the child.

Above is the summary of data we’re going to analyze on.

Initial examination on weight

We’d first look at weight difference between gender at year 2 with factor Antibiotic.

child_obese %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=weight_2yr,group=Gender)) +
  geom_density(aes(color=Gender,fill=Gender),alpha=0.5) +
  xlab("weight (kg)") + ylab("Density (1/kg)") +
  facet_wrap(~Antibiotic)

We can see that in general female tends to be heavier than male and that Antibiotics doesn’t seem to play a huge role in impacting children’s weight.

Then we’d like to check the change between height and weight based on types of Treatment.

child_obese %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=height_2yr, y=weight_2yr, color=Treatment)) +
  stat_smooth() +
  geom_point(alpha=0.1)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

The confidence band for Parenting and Safety Treatment appears to be overlapped except in the range of 87cm - 92cm for height, which means that there’s a significant evidence suggesting that the children within this range differ in their weight. It can be inferred from the graph that children with Parenting Treatment tend to have lighter weight than those with Safety Treatment.

Next, we’d like to count the number of children who are considered as obese at year 2 by using BMI formula weight(kg)/height(m)^2

Calculate BMI

BMI_2yr<-weight_2yr/(height_2yr/100)^2

Determine whether the child is overweight at year 2

child_obese <-
  child_obese %>% 
  mutate(overweight = factor(ifelse(BMI_2yr>18,"Yes","No")))
attach(child_obese)

Examination on overweight

We first check out the proportion of male and female that are considered as obese. We then use boxplot to determine the relationship between child_buccal_fb and overweight, since it is known that buccal_fb ratio plays an important role in obesity.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(Gender,overweight,xlab='Gender',ylab='Overweight')
plot(overweight,child_buccal_fb,ylim=c(0,18),xlab='Overweight',ylab='Child_buccal_fb')

The stacked column chart shows that there are slightly more female considered to be overweight than male. The boxplot indicates that children who’re overweight tend to have higher buccal_fb ratio.

Next, we want to find out the impact of treatment on child obesity.

child_obese %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=Treatment,y=child_buccal_fb)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=overweight), notch=TRUE, position=position_dodge(width=0.8), outlier.size=1, outlier.colour="gray") +
  scale_y_log10()

The notched box and whisker plot represents that children with Safety Treatment tend to have higher buccal_fb ratio than children with Parenting Treatment. Thus there’re more children in Safety Treatment become overweight.

Then we want to determine if child_buccal_fb is related to other variables.

child_obese %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=child_buccal_alpha,y=child_buccal_fb))+
  geom_point()+scale_y_log10()

child_obese %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=child_gut_fb,y=child_buccal_fb))+
  geom_point()+scale_x_log10()+scale_y_log10()

child_obese %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=mom_buccal_fb,y=child_buccal_fb))+
  geom_point()+scale_x_log10()+scale_y_log10()

From the scatter plot, we can notice that there’s a negative correlation between fb ratio and alpha; there’s a positive correlation between buccal fb ratio and gut fb ratio; and there’s no correlation bewteen child_buccal_fb and mom_buccal_fb.

Finally, we want to have an overall picture of the individual variable’s impact on obesity.

mod1 <- rpart(overweight ~ child_buccal_fb+child_buccal_alpha+child_gut_fb+child_gut_alpha+mom_buccal_fb+mom_buccal_alpha, data=child_obese)
fancyRpartPlot(mod1)

It can be inferred from the decision tree that aside from Treatment & Antibiotics, child_buccal_alpha, child_gut_alpha and child_buccal_fb are three most influential variables associated with obesity.

Conclusion

Female tend to have higher weight than male. Obesity is associated with predictors child_buccal_fb, child_buccal_alpha and child_gut_alpha. As child_buccal_fb increases, child_buccal_alpha decreases, child_gut_alpha increases, and the chance of being overweight increases. According to this data, Antibiotics isn’t a major cause in obesity. Parenting can be useful in preventing obesity as children whose parents received nutritiaonal training seem to have lighter weight than those parents who did not.
